author: Messenger Post sports@messengerpostmedia.com
title: AREA ROUNDUP: Midlakes girls soccer wins opening round
text: Posted Oct. 20, 2015 at 10:47 PM By Messenger Post Posted Oct. 20, 2015 at 10:47 PM Canandaigua, N.Y. CLIFTON SPRINGS — The No. 8 Midlakes girls soccer team shut out No. 9 Waterloo 1-0 on Tuesday. Liz Resendiz scored the only goal of the game two minutes into the second half. “The girl’s determination to score paid off within the first two minutes of the second half,” Midlakes coach Shannon Spusta said. “Our goalie, Jen Maslyn, had an outstanding performance and made several critical saves that kept us in the game. Our team is ready to carry the momentum into the next sectional game against Greece Odyssey on Friday.” Jordan Naeye assisted Resendiz off a corner kick. Jen Maslyn made 20 saves and led the Midlakes defense in net. Brianna Hendrix made 17 saves for the Indians in goal. In other high school girls soccer action on Tuesday: CLASS C1 No. 4 Bloomfield 3, No. 13 Oakfield-Alabama 0 Sydney Johnsen scored a goal and had two assists to lead the Bombers to victory. Kimberly Tiffany and Aleta Kent each scored a goal for Bloomfield, and Samantha Rickett made six saves to earn the shutout in net. CLASS C2 No. 3 South Seneca 17, No. 14 Lyons 0 The Falcons took a 9-0 lead into the half and never looked back. Kelsey Shaulis scored three goals and so did Vicki Sturdivant, to help lead South Seneca over the Lions. Morgan McGonigal recorded the shutout in net for the Falcons. BOYS CROSS COUNTRY Waterloo 2-0, Red Jacket 1-1, HAC 0-2 Ben Parrow, Mike Strawberg and Dan Frisbee finished in the top three for Waterloo. Nate Sawyer led Red Jacket with a fifth-place finish, and Rowan Melcher finished in fourth for HAC. Newark 4-0, Marcus Whitman 3-1, Clyde-Savannah 2-2, Wayne 1-3, Mynderse 0-4 Dillon Vandermortel placed first for Newark, while teammates Jarrod Roelands and Brandon Custer finished in third and fourth. Gabe Stash took second place for Marcus Whitman, and Hunter Yates finished in eighth for C-S. Tanner Freida finished in ninth place for Wayne. East Rochester 4-0, Geneva 3-1, Red Creek 2-2, Penn Yan 1-3, Midlakes 0-4 Dawson Bathgate and Ethan Dorrow finished first and second for East Rochester. Patrick Fitzgerald and Aaron Vivlamore finished sixth and seventh for Geneva. Breandon Mantz placed fourth for Red Creek, and Midlakes’ Ben Clements placed ninth. Honeoye 3-0, Williamson 2-1, Lyons 1-2, Sodus 0-3 Jesse Hallett and Zach Erickson took third and fourth for Honeoye, and Williamson’s Tyler Jones placed first. Ethan Dietschler placed second for Lyons. GIRLS CROSS COUNTRY HAC 2-0, Waterloo 1-1, Red Jacket 0-2 Eileen Rienhardt took first place for HAC, and Riley Corey and Sennett Turner took second and third for Waterloo. Katie Cody placed 14th for Red Jacket. Page 2 of 2 - Wayne 4-0, Mynderse 3-1, Clyde-Savannah 2-2, Newark 1-3, Marcus Whitman 0-4 Tara Steensma and Joan Mattle placed second and third for Wayne, and Alivia Arliss placed first for Clyde-Savannah. Olivia Baxter finished in fourth for Mynderse, and Amelia Ennis finished in 12th place for Newark. Geneva 4-0, Midlakes 3-1, Red Creek 2-2, Penn Yan 1-3, East Rochester 0-4 Audra Burrall and Mallorey Fitzgerald took third and fourth place for Geneva, and Amelia Linser finished in sixth place. Chloe Weaver and Sydney Beach finished in first and second for Red Creek. Honeoye 3-0, Williamson 2-1, Lyons 0-2, Sodus 0-2 Mikayla Gullace and Tracy Stutzman took first and second for Honeoye. Mikala Steinmann finished in third for Williamson. GIRLS SWIMMING Canandaigua 104, Hilton 82 Sabrina Turek was a winner in the 500 free and 200 individual medley. Serica Hallstead took first place in diving. GIRLS VOLLEYBALL Lyons 3, Sodus 0 The Lions swept the Spartans 25-17, 25-11 and 25-5. Ayonna McDonald had 19 service points in game three alone with five aces and Teaonna Jenkins added four aces, six digs and three kills. Honeoye 3, Dundee 0 The Bulldogs swept the Scotsmen 25-8, 25-5 and 25-4. Hailey Cornish led Honeoye (14-2) on senior night with 14 aces and 13 assists. Senior Bailey Lis had six kills, and senior Magaret Slocum added five aces. By Messenger Post
